post_text: The Rush-Henrietta Central School District is pleased to present this special reminder of our heartfelt send-off for the resilient Class of 2020. This compilation includes footage from all 12 Rush-Henrietta graduation ceremonies held in June 2020 at Elmer Gordon Stadium. It features important segments from each ceremony, as well as speeches by students and staff members that have not been seen until now. The video concludes with a memorable performance of "Don't Stop Me Now" by the R-H Singers. Thank you for your patience as we pulled this together. We will never forget you, Rush-Henrietta Class of 2020!

post_text:
Preparing for Opening Day!

We know many of you are curious about what our schools will look like this year. Much time and effort has gone into thinking about how best to approach this important task. Our excellent custodial, facilities, and safety teams are putting in long hours to make sure all buildings are ready for the first day of school!

As you look through these photos, you will notice classrooms have been streamlined and area rugs have been removed to help us clean more effectively and efficiently. You'll also see examples of the clear Lexan barriers put into place throughout our schools. In addition, note that the number of seats in each classroom has been reduced by half, allowing physical distancing to occur much more easily. At the Senior High School, for example, the science classrooms and labs have only one chair per table now, instead of two.

There is much more to do, and we know our crews are up to the task. We extend our thanks to each employee for the great work so far!

post_text:
The Kicking Hunger 5K has gone virtual!

The Rush-Henrietta Athletic Association, in conjunction with the Rush-Henrietta Area Food Terminal (RHAFT) and the Town of Henrietta Recreation Department, invite you to participate in the third annual Rush-Henrietta Kicking Hunger 5K. This year, the race will take place virtually anytime between Friday, August 28 and Sunday, August 30. That means you can complete a 5K at any time during that weekend.

Proceeds from the race directly support our community. This year, funds raised will be used to help establish a food pantry at the Good Shepherd Building.

For more information and to register, visit rhnet.org/kickinghunger5k

post_text:
Recent Rush-Henrietta graduate Giovan McKnight was one of three Rochester-area students honored recently by the Frederick Douglass Family Initiative in their blog essay contest. The nationwide contest was aimed at exploring solutions to racial prejudice. Giovan’s entry, “Racism – ‘A Contagious Virus’ ” discusses the idea of racism as a virus, following the assertion put forth by Douglass that racism is a disease.

You can read Giovan’s winning blog entry here: https://fdfi.org/racism-a-contagious-virus/

Congratulations, Giovan!

Summer Reading

Reading during the summer is one of the best ways for students to celebrate all the growth they made as readers and thinkers during the school year. It also helps to keep skills sharp for the upcoming school year!

Our friends at Vollmer Elementary shared some of their favorite book recommendations in this video.

The school websites have information on how to access eBooks. In addition, the Henrietta Public Library offers curbside pickup.

Students entering grades 7-12 can view a list of suggested titles compiled by the R-H librarians at www.rhnet.org/read2020.

Happy reading!

Superintendent’s Choice Art Winners

Each school year, artwork by Rush-Henrietta students in K-12 is selected for display in the district art shows. The art shows for the elementary and junior high school grades were completed prior to the school closure. The Senior High School art show was held online. A few pieces are selected from each of these shows to be framed and displayed in the Parker Administration Building for the following school year. The Superintendent’s Choice Awards ceremony could not be held this year, but we would like to congratulate these students for having their artwork selected for display!

On June 22, Rush-Henrietta held the first-ever Royal Comet Roundup to honor our graduating seniors. The weather was gloomy in the hour before the event, but thankfully there was no rain on this amazing parade! You can see in this video that our seniors had a great time! Thanks to everyone who helped put this together and to those who came out to wave and cheer on the Class of 2020!

The music in this video is “Don’t Stop Me Now,” performed by the R-H Singers! This song also was played at the end of each graduation ceremony, and is a perfect song for this resilient class!

post_text:
Please join the Rush-Henrietta Central School District in thanking each of our retirees for their years of service to our students and our community. Each of our 43 retirees worked for Rush-Henrietta for a minimum of 10 years. While some began their careers in education elsewhere, others have served children here for their entire career. Whether working in a public role or behind the scenes, each employee has worked to better our community.

Although we couldn’t hold a retirement dinner this year, we wish each retiring member of the Rush-Henrietta family much success in the next chapter of their lives! Please join us in doing the same. 💚💛🖤

Each year, one senior is selected from every senior high school in Monroe County to be honored through the Dr. Michael C. O’Laughlin Outstanding Senior Recognition Program. The event was held virtually this year, and a video was aired on Fox Rochester on June 29.

Congratulations to the Rush-Henrietta recipient, Karnavaal Al-Rubayie.
Karnavaal is an honor student with a passion for making realistic art. She is president of National Honor Society, co-president of Interact club, commissioner of Link Crew, and an officer with Natural Helpers. She is also involved in TIES, Diversity Club, U of R STEP, Women's Empowerment, Model UN, and Art Club. She plans to study biomedical engineering at Cornell University and would love to one day work with international humanitarian medical organizations.

You can watch the ceremony here:
https://13wham.com/features/salute-to-the-class-of-2020/salute-to-the-class-of-2020-boces-1-2

Congratulations to Karnavaal and to all the Monroe County seniors recognized this year!

If you attended a Rush-Henrietta graduation ceremony this weekend, you were treated to a unique version of Pomp and Circumstance as our students made their way to their seats on the field.

Local music teachers worked virtually during quarantine to record this special piece to honor the Class of 2020. Nearly 40 music teachers recorded individual parts. Six are from R-H! They are Scott Cannan, Brett Chipman, Sean Joseph, Dave Kluge, Heather Mate, and Kate Rolland.

Thank you all for this incredible gift of music!

post_text:
Introducing the Senior Scavenger Hunt!

Members of the Rush-Henrietta Class of 2020 are invited to participate in this fun senior class activity! This first-of-its-kind Senior Scavenger Hunt is designed to show off your school spirit, help you revisit some fond memories, and get out into the community!

Follow the link to the form, and you will see directions for a series of photos you need to take. For example, one of the tasks is to take a picture with a number 20 – be creative! We will feature some of our favorite photos on Facebook and the senior website.

Make sure you are visible in each of your photos, and upload them through the form. One winner will be randomly selected from all completed submissions to win a donated gift basket! All submissions must be received by 11:59 p.m. Wednesday, June 24. Winner to be announced June 25.

rhnet.org/scavenger

Good luck, be safe, and have fun!

post_text:
Rush-Henrietta Budget, Additional Propositions Approved
Three Incumbents Re-elected to Board of Education

By a wide margin, voters approved the Rush-Henrietta Central School District’s proposed 2020-2021 budget 4,578 to 1,430, an approval rate of 76 percent.

Per Gov. Cuomo’s executive order, counting of ballots began at 5 p.m. The process, held in the Rush-Henrietta Senior High School gym, was completed by 10 p.m. Election inspectors trained by the Monroe County Board of Elections participated in the counting of ballots.

Voters also approved Proposition 2 (bus purchase) 4,818 to 1,204, an approval rate of 80 percent. Proposition 3 (capital reserve) also was approved 4,774 to 1,225, likewise with an 80 percent rate of support.

Three incumbent members of the Board of Education were re-elected. They are Jennifer Laird (5,029), Douglas Rivers (4,979), and Diane McBride (4,884).

These are unofficial results. The Board of Education will certify the results at its next meeting.

We thank the community for its continued support!

Welcome to Rush-Henrietta Senior Days! We kicked off our celebration this weekend with the tribute to our Class of 2020 by the transportation department. If you didn’t see it, be sure to check it out! For the next two weeks, we will have a series of senior-themed posts to honor our graduates.

Today we will get to know some of our students. Each spring, 12th graders at Rush-Henrietta Senior High School make important decisions that will help guide their future. Typically, they celebrate “I Decided” day at school in May with t-shirts announcing their post-high school plans. We shared a video last month featuring those who had made their decisions at that point. However, with the pandemic, many students delayed their decisions until June 1. Students were asked to share their next step with us - and you! - and those who did are featured in this updated "I Decided" video. https://youtu.be/0X_wfFe5QvU

Congratulations to all our seniors as they get ready for the next step!

This year, we introduced the concept of Breakfast with Bo, which gave community members an opportunity to gather at the administration building and hear directly from our superintendent, Mr. Bo Wright. The topic for this spring's Breakfast with Bo was the proposed 2020-2021 budget. However, with schools closed, an in-person event was not possible. Instead, we bring to you what we fondly refer to as Breakfast with Bo: Home Edition. With the help of his daughters - Charlotte, the interviewer, and Maddie, the camera operator - Superintendent Wright answers some of your questions regarding the proposed budget.

Watch for the budget newsletter and ballots to arrive in your mailbox soon, and remember that you must return your mail-in ballot by 5 p.m. June 9.

post_text:
May 18 is the start of Mental Health Awareness Week, just one part of Mental Health Awareness Month throughout May. The global theme for this week is “Kindness,” and people around the world are being encouraged to share their stories about acts of kindness as a way to show that people care. Never underestimate what impact a single kind word or deed can have on someone.

Please remember to take care of yourself, take care of your loved ones, and reach out for help if needed. Our website has a variety of mental wellness resources available, including information on supporting yourself during a crisis. Visit www.rhnet.org/wellness for more information.

Do you have an act of kindness to share? Tell us about it below!

post_text: Each year, graduating Rush-Henrietta seniors participating in music ensembles are honored at the spring concerts. For these students, this is a culmination of many years of practicing and performing – some began playing a musical instrument in fourth grade when they first tried different instruments to find the perfect fit. Others have been singing since before they were in school. Our senior High School concerts take place over three nights in order to allow all our different groups to perform. The first spring concert was scheduled for tonight, May 14. Unfortunately, we won’t be able to hear them perform. However, the music department wanted to honor our seniors, and created this video to highlight them all. These faces show why we are consistently named one of the Best Communities for Music Education.

May 1 is the day that high school seniors across the country typically celebrate their post-graduation plans. In Rush-Henrietta, it has been tradition for the senior class to decorate “I Decided” t-shirts with their college, career, or military plans, and wear the shirts to school on May 1. Of course, this year is different. Many colleges have extended their decision deadlines to June 1, and some of our Class of 2020 may still be weighing their options. But, for those who have committed already, Sara Kimmel asked the students to submit a photo to announce their decisions. While they haven’t received their t-shirts (we will determine how to get them to everyone), the students were told to be creative in announcing their plans. Here is a video she put together featuring the submitted photos.

Please join us in congratulating these seniors from the Rush-Henrietta Class of 2020. (Is your favorite senior not pictured? Don't worry--we have more posts planned for the coming weeks!) 💚💛🖤

Of course, this year is different. Many colleges have extended their decision deadlines to June 1, and some of our Class of 2020 may still be weighing their options. But, for those who have committed already, Sara Kimmel asked the students to submit a photo to announce their decisions. While they haven’t received their t-shirts (we will determine how to get them to everyone), the students were told to be creative in announcing their plans. Here is a video she put together featuring the submitted photos.

Please join us in congratulating these seniors from the Rush-Henrietta Class of 2020. (Is your favorite senior not pictured? Don't worry--we have more posts planned for the coming weeks!) 💚💛🖤

DRIVE.GOOGLE.COM
RH I Decided 2020.mp4

post_text: Senior High School band director Scott Cannan has been learning some new skills! He put together a virtual concert piece using complex audio and video editing software, and the results are spectacular! Cannan contacted more than a dozen other music teachers, and they provided the various parts - several of them playing multiple instruments. Joining Cannan from Rush-Henrietta are Brett Chipman, Sean Joseph, David Kluge, and Heather Mate. Cannan edited all of the submitted recordings into a performance of "Salvation is Created." This is a wonderful example of using this time to learn new skills and find ways to stay connected with others!

post_text:
Don't forget to tell us about your science activities! Raina from Sherman shared this one: "I did a science experiment yesterday, and I am planning on doing another one today. We have a bunch of old science kits at home from when we were little, so I used one of those to make crystals! They are called jiggly crystals, and they are crystals but they are soft and squishy. I made 3 colors: Red, Blue, and Purple. i made the red by using citric acid, and the blue by using baking soda! Then, I mixed 1/2 of each together to make purple! Today, I`m going to put all my crystals into a test tube then add red cabbage powder (I know it sounds strange, but it interacts with the citric acid and baking soda) to make a sunrise crystal, which is pink, blue, and purple. it is really cool! It worked just liked I hoped it would, and I really enjoyed doing it."

That sounds like a great experiment, Raina!

Many thanks to Dr. Tanski and all of the health care workers who are putting themselves at risk to help others.

post_text:
For the 11th consecutive year - and the 15th time overall - Rush-Henrietta Central School District has been honored with the Best Communities for Music Education designation from The NAMM Foundation for outstanding commitment to music education.

Now in its 21st year, the Best Communities for Music Education designation is awarded to districts that demonstrate outstanding achievement in efforts to provide music access and education to all students. To qualify for the Best Communities designation, Rush-Henrietta met criteria concerning funding, graduation requirements, music class participation, instruction time, facilities, and support for the music programs.

This national award recognizes that Rush-Henrietta is leading the way with learning opportunities for students, including music and the arts as important elements of a well-rounded education.

Thank you for your support of our outstanding music programs!

To encourage students to remain actively engaged in a variety of learning experiences, Superintendent Bo Wright will be posting different challenges that appeal to all ages. post_text:
Two important updates to our free meals program!

Starting today, Monday, March 23, we have a change in location. The program experienced low usage at the Rustic Village location last week, so that site has been closed. Instead, the district has added a new location at Crane Elementary School, 85 Shell Edge Drive, Henrietta.

In addition, we heard you! We took your feedback seriously when you asked if it was possible to pick up breakfast and lunch at the same time. Good news--this required a state waiver and that permission has been granted! Each of our five locations will now be open from 9 to 11 a.m. We will be able to provide you with both breakfast and lunch during that single visit!

Many thanks to all of the district employees and the many volunteers who have helped make this program a big success. We couldn't do it without you!

Hello, Rush-Henrietta! This is a reminder that grab-and-go breakfast and lunch meals for children age 18 and younger are available starting today. The meals are being provided free of charge at four locations while schools are closed due to the coronavirus.

Breakfast is available weekdays from 9 to 9:30 am, and lunch is available from noon to 12:30 p.m. Meals are available at the Henrietta Senior Center, Riverton Knolls, Stonewood Village Apartments, and a drive-up location at the Senior High School.

Here are some pictures of the meals being handed out this morning. Don't be shy. We look forward to serving you!

post_text:
How about some good news?

Construction on the new, more secure entrances at Crane, Leary, and Winslow is moving right along! In fact, both Crane and Leary have moved into their new main office space, and Winslow should be moving into their space soon. The temporary entrances at each building will remain in use through the end of the school year while the exterior work is completed through this spring.

The old main office areas are being converted into additional offices and flexible work space. We expect all work to be completed and the new entrances to open this summer.

As part of continued efforts to make our schools as safe as possible for students, the Rush-Henrietta Central School District will hold safety drills as part of Safety Week during the week of March 9. These drills are designed to practice and assess how well we would respond during an emergency.

A number of activities are scheduled to occur throughout the district between March 9 and 13, including bus safety drills. Most of the bus drills will occur upon arrival at school, but please be aware that normal bus schedules may be off by a few minutes during the week.

To learn more about all of the safety week activities, visit www.rhnet.org/safetyweeknews.

Also, please plan to join us for the District Safety Forum, 6:30 p.m. on April 29! It will be held in the cafeteria of the Senior High School, 1799 Lehigh Station Road, Henrietta.

post_text:
New teachers in Rush-Henrietta participate in a program that provides workshops on a variety of topics throughout their first year. On March 3, the teachers participated in a discussion on equity and inclusion. Led by Director of Wellness and Equity Diane Wynne along with Director of Professional Development Dominic Piacentini, the attendees learned about Glenn Singleton's Four Agreements of Courageous Conversations About Race, the Cultural Competency Continuum, and reflected upon how equity-related topics impact their work with students each and every day.

Recognizing the many kinds of diversity that exist within our school community, we are committed to strengthening the connection among culture, teaching, learning, and achievement. Equity and inclusion is one of our district priorities, and workshops such as this one help to ensure that our programs and learning environments support this important initiative.

National School Social Work Week, March 1-7

Please join us in thanking our school social workers for all they do each day to support our students in Rush-Henrietta! This week highlights the vital role that school social workers have in helping students meet academic, social, and emotional challenges. School social workers focus on the whole child, linking families to community resources and working to improve school culture and climate by building supportive and trusting relationships with students and families. Thank you!

Universal Prekindergarten students in the afternoon sessions at Good Shepherd were treated to a special weather presentation by 13-WHAM Meteorologist Scott Hetsko on Tuesday, Feb. 25. He talked to them about different kinds of weather and even made a cloud in a bottle to demonstrate how clouds form. The classes were amazed by videos he showed of past blizzards in Rochester and were eager to share what they like to do in snow. They were a little disappointed to learn that today’s weather was going to be more wind than snow!

Tuesday, Feb. 25, marked the 100th day of school in Rush-Henrietta! There were many celebrations at our elementary schools, including Fyle Elementary, which marked the occasion with fun, engaging activities throughout the day. Teachers planned 100-themed activities such as building a tower out of 100 cups and creating bridges with 100 toothpicks and 100 marshmallows. Fyle also won a beautiful 100th day lawn sign from Card My Yard, which was set up to welcome students in the morning. Everyone had a blast getting great class photos with the sign as well as with the special 100th day photo booth. It was a great day filled with fun, learning, and laughter!

The Office of Special Education is hosting an informational meeting 6-7 p.m. Monday, March 2. Parents and guardians who are interested in learning more about special education services in Rush-Henrietta are invited to join us at the Transportation and Operations Center, 1133 Lehigh Station Road, Henrietta.

Director of Special Education Jessica Bailey, along with Coordinators of Special Education Jennifer Cardinale and David Patt, will discuss special education services, the Extended School Year program, helping your child transition to the next grade or building, and graduation pathways.

We hope that you will be able to join us to learn more about special education in Rush-Henrietta.

post_text:
Two Senior High School students won a contest by honoring their mentors!

After reading Markus Zusak’s book about a reluctant hero, I Am the Messenger, students in Lynn Marquart's class discussed what makes a hero, how we choose our personal heroes, and who can be a hero.

The seniors then selected someone they felt was an inspiration to them or to humanity in general and created both a written piece and a performance piece (audio, art, video, written) that honored the person they chose. These projects were submitted to the website MyHero.com, a non-profit organization that celebrates the positive impact that people can have in the world. Two of the students entered a contest on the website about mentors, and they won!

Congratulations to McKenna Light and Zach Kroesen! You can read their essays and learn more about the special people they profiled as their mentors here:
https://myhero.com/my-mentor-bob-swaisgood
https://myhero.com/terry-fyke

post_text:
The Rush-Henrietta boys varsity bowling team is heading to the New York State Bowling Tournament after winning the Section V title today at AMF Gates Lanes in Rochester!

The varsity bowling squad consists of Parker Hoyt, Parker Hunt, Jake Shuboney, Keaton Ostrowski, Raymond Hill, Jacob Shoemaker, Lucas Teeples, Kyle Dion, Tyler Bliek, and Joey DiGioia.

The team, which also won the Monroe County division championship this year, is led by Brian Usselman, a math teacher at Rush-Henrietta Senior High School. He coached bowling from 1999 to 2009, and took the helm again this year. "What a way to return!" Usselman says. "These athletes are the definition of team. When one player is struggling, the rest of the team finds a way to pick them up. I am very proud of their perseverance and determination."

State competition will be held March 15 in Syracuse. We hope you bowl over the competition! The Rush-Henrietta athletics program continues to make us proud. We appreciate the community's continued support!

We visited Burger Junior High School on a snowy day in February, and had a chance to visit many classrooms throughout the day. The 670 students at Burger start each morning with a song of the day—the day’s selection was “I’m a Believer,” in honor of the school’s upcoming musical, Shrek JR. The administration and staff in the building focus on making it a welcoming place for all students. Inspirational banners and student art displays line the halls, while the main foyer offers a display of flags honoring the many countries Burger students are from.

Be sure to read the captions with each photo to learn more about what our students were engaged in!

Our Day in the Life series offers a peek behind the scenes of a different school each month to showcase some of the great things happening in our district every school day. If you missed them, be sure to visit the albums for the Senior High School, Roth Junior High, Crane, and Sherman Elementary visits. Links to each one may be found at rhnet.org/dayinthelife.

post_text: Nearly 50 Burger Junior High School students and staff braved the icy waters of Lake Ontario for the Twentieth Annual Polar Plunge for Special Olympics this past Sunday, February 9. The brave members of the Burger Outdoor Club waded, ran, and jumped into the 34 degree water joining more than 1,800 others in raising money to support the programs and services of Special Olympics New York. The team was recognized as one of the top ten fundraisers, contributing more than $5,000 to the cause. Overall, the event raised close to $275,000. Team members say they are looking forward to Freezin’ for a Reason for a third time next year!

For Rush-Henrietta Senior High School’s Parker Hoyt, bowling is more than a fun game. In the seven years that Parker has been bowling, he has had five career 300 games! In fact, two of those games have happened this season on the varsity bowling team. A 300 means that the bowler has bowled 12 strikes in a row—a perfect game.

As a freshman, Parker broke the Rush-Henrietta bowling record with a 764 series, and was named to the All-Greater Rochester and first-team All Monroe County Boys Bowling teams. After this last match of the 2020 season, he now holds the new record with an 805 series. Shown here with coach Brian Usselman, he has led the Rush-Henrietta bowling team to two victories at the Section VI Buffalo Invitational tournament. Overall, Parker has held a 228 bowling average through hard work and dedication to the sport.

Way to go, Parker!

post_text: Senior High School students in Mrs. Daley’s and Mrs. Pfluke’s health classes collected donations for Joyful Rescues Inc. as part of a community service project. The classes wanted to participate in a community service activity, and chose Joyful Rescues. In December and early January, the students collected items from the non-profit organization’s wish list. The classes even had a friendly competition to see which one could collect the most, winning a pizza party and a chance to meet the dogs of the rescue group. In addition to collecting several boxes and bags full of needed items, students and staff donated $100 to the rescue, and were able to meet some of the volunteers and dogs when they came to collect the donations. Dr. Shafer even brought his dog in for the event!

Emily Connell, a graduate of the Rush-Henrietta Central School District, is the valedictorian of the Misericordia University winter commencement class of 2019! Emily had a 4.0 GPA and will pursue her graduate education at Misericordia University in its Doctor of Physical Therapy program.

Emily is the daughter of Dennis and Jodi Connell, of Rush. Jodi, who works at Crane Elementary School, has spent 16 years in the district as a speech language pathologist. Congratulations to Emily and the Connell family!

post_text:
Students in Mrs. Akers' sixth grade science class at Vollmer Elementary School recently competed against their teacher by constructing a thermal energy device that minimizes the amount of thermal energy transferred. Using common materials such as foil, paper towel, tape and other insulating materials, students tried to create a device that was more effective than their teacher’s!

Most groups were able to beat the teacher's device due to their innovative use of insulators! The class discussed common variables that made a difference in the success of their device such as what their original container for the water was, the types of insulators they used, how many layers they used to insulate the device, whether or not they left the cap off the device too long before measuring the final temperature, or if they overheated the water to begin with. These variables made a difference in the transfer of heat energy, and students discussed how they could use this information to improve their devices in the future.

January 16 at 5:59 PM ·

Ninth-graders in Mr. Prinzi’s Pre-AP World History classes at Roth Junior High School recently held mock trials as part of their study of the Roman Empire. After learning about the famous death of Julius Caesar, the students decided to put one of his killers, Marcus Brutus, on trial.

Was Brutus justified in the killing of Julius Caesar to save the Roman Republic? Each student served as either a defense lawyer, prosecuting lawyer, judge, bailiff, witness, or member of the jury. The lawyers prepared their opening statements, called witnesses to the stand, and argued their cases! The students did an absolutely fantastic job making their arguments.

Et tu, Brute? In both classes, the prosecution won, and Brutus was found guilty of murder!
